properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Persistent flurries are expected to develop early on Thursday with occasional snow squalls. Very strong winds and falling temperatures may combine with fresh snowfall to cause reduced visibility in blowing snow over some areas. Snowfall accumulations of 2 to 4 cm can be expected on Thursday with a further 2 to 4 cm Thursday night. Flurries and the potential for snow squalls will persist into Friday. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High Storm Surge levels and large waves are expected to impact the coast. Blanc-Sablon: 2019-04-04, from 08:30 AM to 11:30 AM. Blanc-Sablon: 2019-04-04, from 8:30 PM to 11:30 PM. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. It will give 25 to 40 centimetres of snow by Thursday morning over the Lower North Shore. The Chevery and Blanc Sablon regions may experience a brief period of freezing rain this evening or early tonight. Behind the storm, high westerly winds gusting to 100 km/h will develop and reduce visibilities in blowing snow. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Snow at times heavy will develop later this evening or after midnight then taper off to flurries Thursday morning, with flurries continuing through Thursday night. At this time, snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm are expected along the coast with amounts as high as 40 cm expected inland and over higher terrain. Strong east to southeasterly winds will develop tonight, with gusts to 100 km/h along parts of the coast early Thursday. The southeasterly winds will shift to southwesterly winds with gusts to 110 km/h Thursday morning. These gusty winds combined with the heavy snow will result in reduced visibilities in blowing snow. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Persistent snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Persistent flurries and snow squalls are expected to develop early on Thursday and persist into Friday. Very strong winds and falling temperatures will combine with fresh snowfall to cause intermittent blizzard-like conditions over some areas. Snowfall accumulations between 5 and 15 cm can be expected by Thursday evening, with similar amounts again on Thursday night. Flurries and snow squalls will persist on Friday. Although winds may be slightly weaker, visibility is not likely to improve until Friday evening when flurries are expected to dissipate. Further snowfall accumulations are possible. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
